334. To DOMENICO GRIMANI.

Damiani Elegeia f0. G4. v0. London. B. f0. b²z F. p. 74 ι HN: Lond. ii. 2: LB. 167. (15 May> 1515.

[Plainly contemporary with Ep. 333, with which it is almost identical in tenor 3 and doubtless expanded for publication to the same extent. The month- date may be altered to bring it into accord. Grimani’s reply was kept by Ammonius with the other documents from Rome which he decided to retain (cf. Ep. 338 introd.) 3 and failed subsequently to reach Erasmus (Lond. iii. 11 and v. 26, LB. 315 and 331) in spite of the urgent entreaties which he addressed to Ammonius’ kinsman and executor (LB. App. 228, 260, 132, 281).

Domenico Grimani (19 Feb. 1461—27 Aug. 1523) was the son of Antonio Grimani, who from being an exiled general of the Republic became Doge in 1521. Domenico, who was created Cardinal in 1493, and Pati-iarah of Aquileia 1498, shared his father’s exile at Rome, and rose to be Cardinal Bp. of Porto, second only to Raffaelle Riario. He was a patron of literature, and his rich collections of MSS. now form part of the Library of St. Mark's at Venice. Erasmus addressed to him his Paraphrase on St. Paul's Epistle to the Romans, Louvain, Th. Martens, Nov. 1517. See Ciaconius iii. 180, 1 and NBG.]
